{"_id":"AFdiqi641ypuP3QX","name":"The Vor Layder Sceptre","content":"<div style=\"font-family:Signika;text-align:justify;font-size:14px;margin-top:2rem;margin-left:2rem\">\n<p>The Sceptre was split into 3 separate pieces. @JournalEntry[8JGZ9h5FCMEPvlxU]{Osric van der Haan} has provided the following information.</p>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Jewel</strong>. The green jewel that formed the centre of the sceptre's head is otherwise known as @JournalEntry[Of1qZaEFgem9VTKB]{The Lost Heart of O'Shan}. This jewel is thought to have been found and cut by a @JournalEntry[fj21otTBB5oc6Dcs]{Meredin} jewel smith by the name of @JournalEntry[QRPyd13l2mylCV3P]{Jas'mar Sokur}. Sokur was a follower of the ancient Meredin goddess @JournalEntry[jjZVEFlbu7br7i8N]{O'Shan}. He named the jewel in reference to one of the ancient tales of O'Shan. He presented it to the then emperor of Meredin as a gift. The emperor was pleased but had Sokur beheaded as he did not want him crafting one that could possibly outdo the Heart and the emperor must have the best in the world. Sokur's work is highly sought after.</li>\n<li><strong>The Head</strong>. The head itself is a gold latticed casement which opens and has a setting in which to place the jewel. It has long been thought that this was made by the legendary goldsmith @JournalEntry[o0eRvO1SBCExUd3P]{T'Vran Malgrave}. In general, pieces by him are sought after and would, if provenance could be verified, be worth an insane amount of money. Its history is less clear than the Heart. Malgrave was also from Meredin. This piece of work was more than likely made before the Heart. It may well have been the emperors collection for some time before he was presented with the Heart.</li>\n<li><strong>The Staff</strong>. This has a setting at one end that will accept the head of the Sceptre. The staff is made from an ancient Yew Tree, that as far as Osric knows is still living. Many rumours abound as to its whereabouts but that is not the focus of this task. The people of Meredin believed in opposing forces coming together to become something more powerful due to that conflict. The staff made from the Yew Tree is very much a passive earth energy. While the Heart is also of the earth it at some point was imbued with conflicting magic. These two put together and amplified by the golden lattice made the Sceptre very powerful.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p>The then emperor of Meredin, @JournalEntry[kGzxoTVtwR3Edq3i]{Pir'Lanash}, was not entirely sane and he studied the dark magics which led him to put these three elements together. With the Sceptre he maintained power long after he would naturally have died. His reign was not a pleasant one either. Finally he was taken down and the Sceptre broken and the pieces lost. But there have always been clues for those who knew where to look. Fortunately those people are very very few. Osric is dubious about finding all the pieces again but unless the Sceptre needs the wielding of those ancient magicks and they have been lost. No-one now lives who understands them.</p>\n<p>Osric has since stated that the meaning of Vor Layder in the ancient languages is <strong>'Stone of Dread and Fear'</strong>.</p>\n</div>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"y4pRACjo50IZ62pc":3},"flags":{}}
