{"_id":"vYRkdW1ucu1zyU3V","name":"Cassandra's Journal","content":"<div style=\"font-family:Signika;text-align:justify;font-size:14px;margin-top:2rem;margin-left:2rem\">\n<p>In a locked drawer in the desk is where Cassandra's journal, at least part of it, is found. There are entries for most days for a while but the following entries are the most relevant.</p>\n<p>Indeed quite a lot of the things that she has written are ramblings of someone one might consider not quite stable.</p>\n<p>In her journal she talks about her search for <strong>\"Seven of Twelve\"</strong></p>\n<p>She has outlined her endeavours in doing this. She states that she has searched in many places curiously her ones related to Sanseer, her home city, engender some gruesome reading.</p>\n<p>Â </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I have interrogated many of the so-called intelligentsia in Sanseer. They are all fools. These scum give out that they have deep knowledge of hidden things but turn out to be charlatans all.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Some of her notes mention specific people.</p>\n<h2>Ester Horn</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This useless weasel purported to be a witch, casting bones and living in semi-darkness in a hovel lit by black candles and fires made from 'strange' herbs. Naturally turned out to be fake. Her misery as I killed her wasn't however. Woman knew nothing of use.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr />\n<h2>Cornell Thomas</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This fool was a supposed bibliophile. Had a very large collection of books and bought and sold them. In addition was reported in the 'right' circles to have a cache of tomes more esoteric in nature. Some of his books were useful but for other purposes than the one at hand - some interesting magicks. It was almost a shame when I gutted him like a rat.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr />\n<h2>Quentin Farrell</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yet another book dealer specialising in ancient tomes. Nicknamed him Quentin the Quiverer he shook so much. Had hardly asked him more than a few questions before I grew fatigued at this useless fool. Quelled his quivering by cutting his throat, slowly.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr />\n<h2>Marta Lyle</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Knew nothing truly important. How that can be for someone who was purported to be a scryer escapes me. I'll never understand people's aversion to torture, it always seems to work for me. I didn't really need to put this woman on the rack (amongst other things) but it was pleasant to cause some unnecessary pain. Eviscerating her was satisfying too. She did spill some beans however, prior to spilling her guts that is. Spluttered out the name of a man in Halith in the end, one Doren con Grath, who she thought might have more information. Don';t know if she thought that would save her. Ah, the deluded hopes of the weak.</p>\n<p>Â </p>\n<p>Â </p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p>Sent one of the minor acolytes to Halith to pull the information from Grath. These worms are always looking to please and climb the ladder. Well, I let them try. It pleases me to see them writhing around trying to get the better of each other. Probably lose more of these little piss ants to playing that game than to a bloody battle. I gave the worm some explicit instructions as to how Doren con Grath should die after he had talked. I want certain deaths to be known to be the will of the Twelve. The cretin let him live - or at least let him escape which is the same thing - forcing me to send another. Seeing as the shit-stain had come back empty-handed I slowly cut his hands off as an object lesson. His wailing as a result of this punishment became too much, so I roasted him on a spit for the others to see.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p>The second cretinous worm I sent to Halith actually managed to surmount his mental deficiencies and return with some useful information - and the head of Doren con Grath. I think he was looking to gain some favour with this little embellishment to my plan. I considered relieving him of his own head but decided against it. After all he got the job done. Call it a whimsy.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p>It seems further clues lie in Perdingham.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p>If it were not for Grath's information, I would not be in this dripping, stinking den, surrounded by fools. What's more that detestable, licentious man Victor Drayton has come here. Smells like a brewery. If I had not required him I would not be in this hideous position of having to open my legs to him to keep him on-side. At least the sacrifice of that 'pure as snow' daughter of mine should cleanse me of Drayton';s inebriated and inept fumblings. I do not yet know if he has worked out he will soon be a loose end. His sexual predilections have now stretched to my daughter to the point that he thinks that she is his reward. Plans to flee to Sha-Ren Tar I believe. This man's ridiculousness could almost make me laugh and vomit simultaneously.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p>So now to discover - or re-discover Perdingham. The village was âlost'; an age ago in Norgorber knows what calamity. Somewhere in these accursed mountains it lies. And apparently in eternal night, although that may be just a clichÃ©.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p>The day approaches. Oh so pretty Holly will die under my blades and I will subsume her life and her youth. Then I'll put a cat amongst the pigeons of the Twelve.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</div>","img":null,"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"y4pRACjo50IZ62pc":3},"flags":{}}
