{"_id":"xAaEjSB5jOkYcJnX","name":"The Houses of Keron","content":"<div style=\"font-family:Signika;text-align:justify;font-size:14px;margin-top:2rem;margin-left:2rem\">\n<h1>The Eight Houses of Keron (Incomplete)</h1>\n<h2>Blenerhayset</h2>\n<p>This is the ruling family, not just of the continent of Keron, but of all Ash Keron. The family resides in the city of Ash Garon, the effective capital city of Ash Keron. All other families defer to them.Â </p>\n<h2>Brakefield</h2>\n<p>The Brakefields have had their lands in and around Sanseer for generations. Their reach extends northwards to the (location here) and southwards to encompass the large town of Halith. Westward, the Brakefields have influence to around the halfway point of the continent. Beyond that point, House Claybrook holds sway. There have long been petty disputes between these two families, although some general truce is in existence.</p>\n<h2>Claybrook</h2>\n<p>The Claybrooks are a relatively less powerful family. Their lands do not extend much northwards or southwards. They do however have responsibility for and control the port of Ragarth (the family seat). This port connects directly to the second continent of San Katarin. The family is generally held to be aggrieved by the lower status they hold despite the importance of their involvement in trade with San Katarin. This trade is the source of their wealth.</p>\n<hr />\n<h3>Bettesthorne</h3>\n<h3>Estney</h3>\n<h3>Fletewoode</h3>\n<h3>Goodryke</h3>\n<h3>Wade</h3>\n</div>","img":"modules/sanseer/media/journals/houses/keron-houses.png","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"y4pRACjo50IZ62pc":3},"flags":{}}
{"_id":"xWZqIoUGU6ytLm8L","name":"Allan Inglis","content":"<div style=\"font-family:Signika;text-align:justify;font-size:14px;margin-top:2rem;margin-left:2rem\">\n<div><img style=\"border-radius:50%;border:2px solid black;box-shadow:0 0 25px #484444\" src=\"modules/sanseer/media/journals/characters/close-ups/inglis-allan.jpg\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></div>\n<hr />\n<p>A smuggler based in and around the 'port' area of Barnard.</p>\n<p>According to Melvin Craddock (a self-confessed rival of Inglis) Inglis' men were seen escorting a cloaked and hooded young woman that reasonably matched the description of Holly Brakefield into a well known establishment in Barnard called The Marshall of Kesh.</p>\n<p>The young woman was described as being of fair skin, well dressed and had long dark auburn hair.</p>\n<h2>San Florali</h2>\n<p>Having encountered Allan Inglis in the village of San Florani, one of his 'hideouts', he appears to be a man who can be trusted. His has acquaintance with Holly Brakefield as he has done business with and for her grandfather, Godfrey Brakefield. He likes Holly, believing her to be the best of the family.</p>\n<p>He has denied the accounts of Holly being at the Marshall of Kesh, another one of his enterprises stations. He had been suspicious of The Innkeeper for some while. Not only was the man rather strange but he was skimming more than Inglis would reasonably expect a factor to skim. He was having him surveilled but his men kept losing him round corners and bends with the strange man having left no clue as to where he had gone.</p>\n<p>Inglis has given you advice that the family Claybrook may be involved in Holly's abduction. There was much rivalry between the Brakefields and the Claybrooks in the past and while Godfrey and Old Man Claybrook had ironed out differences and come to a truce, it is certain that Evan Claybrook was not happy with the new arrangements. Possibly some of his brothers felt similarly.</p>\n<p>Inglis view of Evan Claybrook is that he is a sloppy operator and could well have made mistakes and left an evidence trail. Whether this can be seen around Ragarth, e.g. rumours in inns, people he may have engaged in the abduction or more likely somewhere in Claybrook Hall he cannot truly say.</p>\n<p>He cannot commit to the certainty that the Claybrooks are involved, however he did say that the Claybrooks keep a close eye on the Brakefields regardless. And that means that there is likely evidence at the Hall of whatever happened to Holly, even if they were not the culprits themselves.</p>\n</div>","img":"modules/sanseer/media/journals/characters/portraits/inglis-allan.jpg","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"y4pRACjo50IZ62pc":3},"flags":{}}
